His having formed and ani- mated a man, refers to his having taught the barbarous people, among whom he settled, to lead a more civilised life. Sir Isaac Newton makes Prometheus a nephew of Sesotris, the Egyptian king, and to have been left by him on Mount Caucasus with a body of troops, in order to guard his conquests in that quarter. Some make him the same with Noah, an opinion which Bryant adopts. Le Clerc supposes him to have been the same with Magog. The truth, however, appears to be, that Pro- metheus is in some way connected with the mythology of India, and the progress of religion from east to west.
